diff:1619319182:1619319182:=1,56d0%0a%3c :Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild%0a%3c :Essential: {Category.LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild$:essential}%0a%3c :Title: Accents in My Fair Lady%0a%3c :Author: lauray%0a%3c :Section: D%0a%3c :Completed: 24.04.2021 - 19:53%0a%3c :Status: ungraded%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#history]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#historyend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c %25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#comments]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#commentsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c !!%0a%3c %0a%3c Summary: \\%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summary]]%0a%3c %0a%3c How the Cockney accent is perceived as low-class and vulgar in the film, My Fair Lady%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summaryends]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c [[#content]]%0a%3c %0a%3c Video from My Fair Lady: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EAYUuspQ6BY&ab_channel=shanmugamlakshmanan %0a%3c %0a%3c In the movie, My Fair Lady, the main character is looked down on because of her accent. The Cockney accent she used was considered a lower class accent and less proper than the standard Received Pronunciation or “Queen’s English” accent.%0a%3c %0a%3c Some key elements of her accent that were criticized was the glottal stopping used in words like “where”, “you”, “going” and “better” which are pronounced with a glottal stop, making better into [be?ə] instead of pronouncing the ‘t’ at the alveolar. Another criticized element of her accent was what is known as the “London vowel shift” where “day” is pronounced as [dæɪ] instead of [deɪ]. %0a%3c %0a%3c This is not really a dialect of English but more of just an accent that is typically centralized around London, specifically the East End. One of the characters in the film, Professor Higgins, believes that accent and tone determines people’s prospects in society. He takes on Eliza and is determined to “fix” her and make her into a “proper lady” showing his disdain for her original Cockney accent and that he didn’t think that she had a chance in “society”. This is a more dated example of linguistic discrimination, but shows how accents were taken to signify a person’s place in society as well as the difficulty to move out of that position because of their accent.%0a%3c %0a%3c Sources:%0a%3c https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/My_Fair_Lady_(film)%0a%3c http://dialectblog.com/british-accents/%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
